Introduction:

Music streaming platforms like Spotify have become central to how people discover and consume music globally. However, the factors that make a song successful on these platforms remain unclear to artists and producers. This analysis explores what audio characteristics drive streaming popularity by examining data from Spotify's top 2023 songs alongside TikTok metrics.

Key Research Questions:

  • Which audio features (loudness, energy, danceability) are associated with higher streaming counts?
  • Is listener attention concentrated among a few dominant artists?
  • Can we predict a song's virality potential based on its audio characteristics?

Understanding these patterns will help artists and producers optimize their music for streaming success and provide data-driven insights into listener preferences.

Data Curation

Our analysis integrates data from three primary sources:

  • Spotify Top Songs of 2023 (top_spotify_songs_2023.csv): This dataset provides streaming numbers, chart positions, and core audio features (e.g., loudness, energy) for the top songs of 2023.
  • TikTok Popularity (tiktok_popularity.csv): This dataset offers complementary metrics related to TikTok virality and additional audio features.
  • Spotify Tracks with YouTube Metrics (song_tracks.csv): This is a comprehensive dataset containing detailed audio features along with external metrics like YouTube views, likes, and comments for a large collection of songs. This is useful for providing a broader context and potentially training more robust machine learning models to identify virality elements beyond the top charts.

Data preprocessing

In this section we load the three datasets into pandas DataFrames using the read_csv function. We print the shape of each dataset so we can confirm that the data loaded correctly and to get an idea of how many songs and features we are working with.

Next, we clean the column names by making them lowercase and replacing spaces with underscores. This makes the data easier to use in Python because the column names become simpler and more consistent. After that, we rename the main song and artist columns so that both datasets use the same names. This step matters because it will allow us to join or compare the datasets later without running into naming problems. To make sure the cleaning process worked, we print the first few rows of each dataset. This helps us see what the data looks like and check that important features like streaming numbers, playlist counts, danceability, energy, and loudness are present. It also gives us an early sense of how the Spotify and TikTok datasets differ.

We then merge the Spotify and TikTok datasets together using an inner join on the common columns, "song" and "artist", to create a single merged_df. This makes sure that every song we analyze has both Spotify and TikTok information. After merging, we remove any duplicate columns that came from combining the two datasets.

Next, we clean the crucial "streams" column, removing commas and converting it to a numeric data type, as this is essential for machine learning models and statistical analysis. We then select and convert other key audio features we want to study ("danceability", "energy", "loudness", mode, key) to numeric types.

We check which of these features actually exist in the merged dataset and convert those columns into numeric values as well. After that, we remove any rows that are missing values for streams or the selected audio features. This leaves us with a clean dataset that is ready for analysis. At the end of this step, we print the number of songs left and the list of features we are analyzing.

In[]:
merged_df = pd.merge(spotify23_df, tiktok_df, on=["song", "artist"], how="inner")
merged_df = merged_df.loc[:, ~merged_df.columns.duplicated()].copy()
if "streams" in merged_df.columns:
    merged_df["streams"] = (
        merged_df["streams"]
        .astype(str)
        .replace(",", "", regex=True)
        .replace("nan", None)
    )
    merged_df["streams"] = pd.to_numeric(merged_df["streams"])
features = ["danceability", "energy", "loudness", "mode", "key"]
available_features = [f for f in features if f in merged_df.columns]
for col in available_features:
    merged_df[col] = pd.to_numeric(merged_df[col], errors="coerce")
merged_df.head()
merged_df = merged_df.dropna(subset=["streams"] + available_features)
print(f"Clean merged dataset: {merged_df.shape[0]} songs")
print("Analyzing features:", available_features)

After cleaning the data, we create a bar chart to show the top ten artists based on total Spotify streams. We group the dataset by artist and add up all the streams for each artist. Then we sort the artists from highest to lowest total streams and select the top ten.

The bar chart shows which artists dominate total streaming numbers. This helps us answer one of our main questions about whether streaming attention is spread evenly or focused on a small group of performers. From the graph, we can clearly see that a few artists such as The Weeknd and Olivia Rodrigo have much higher total streams than most others.

This visualization is important because it shows how unequal music popularity can be in the streaming industry. It also supports our broader analysis of how artist dominance plays a role in song success.

Figure 2: Energy vs. Streams

Results

The regression results show that loudness has a stronger and statistically significant relationship with Spotify streams (R = 0.119, p = 0.0315), while energy shows a weaker and non-significant correlation (R = 0.047, p = 0.1854). This suggests that louder tracks tend to receive more streams, possibly due to their higher perceived intensity and production quality. However, energy alone does not strongly predict popularity, indicating that other musical or external factors likely play a larger role in determining a song's streaming success.

Danceability measures how easy a song is to dance to, based on beat, rhythm, and tempo. Energy reflects a track's intensity and activity, and fast, loud, or dynamic songs score higher. Loudness is the overall volume in decibels, showing how loud a song sounds.

merged_df["danceability_bin"] = pd.cut(
    merged_df["danceability"], bins=3, labels=["Low", "Medium", "High"]
)
merged_df["streams_bin"] = pd.qcut(
    merged_df["streams"], q=3, labels=["Low", "Medium", "High"]
)
contingency = pd.crosstab(merged_df["danceability_bin"], merged_df["streams_bin"])
print("\nContingency Table:\n")
print(contingency)
chi2, p, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(contingency)

print("\nChi-Squared Test Results:")
print(f"Chi Statistic = {chi2:.3f}")
print(f"Degrees of Freedom = {dof}")
print(f"P-value = {p:.4f}")
plt.figure(figsize=(7,5))

sns.heatmap(
    contingency,
    annot=True,
    cmap="crest",
    fmt="d",
    linewidths=1.5,
    linecolor="white",
    cbar=True
)

plt.title(
    "Danceability vs Streams (Chi-Squared Test)\n"
    f"Chi = {chi2:.2f},  p = {p:.4f}",
    fontsize=16, weight="bold"
)

plt.xlabel("Streams Category", fontsize=13, weight="semibold")
plt.ylabel("Danceability Category", fontsize=13, weight="semibold")

plt.yticks(fontsize=11)

Figure 3: Danceability vs. Streams (Chi-Squared)

The above heatmap shows relatively even distribution across all categories, confirming no significant association between danceability levels and streaming success.

Hypotheses

Null Hypothesis (H): There is no association between a song's danceability level and its Spotify stream category.

Alternative Hypothesis (H): There is an association between a song's danceability level and its Spotify stream category.

Conclusion

Since the Chi-Squared test produced a p-value of 0.5584, which is greater than 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. This means there is no statistically significant relationship between a song's danceability category and its popularity (measured by streams) - danceability alone does not appear to influence how often a song is streamed on Spotify.

Primary Analysis

To investigate our final question, we developed a machine learning classification model using the larger Spotify Tracks with YouTube Metrics dataset to predict binary "virality" based on audio features. A song was labeled "viral" (Class 1) if its Spotify streams were in the top 20% (80th percentile) of the dataset. This resulted in an imbalanced dataset: 16,475 non-viral songs (Class 0) and 4,119 viral songs (Class 1). We used SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Over-sampling Technique) to address this imbalance in the training data and trained a Random Forest Classifier.

We chose the Random Forest Classifier for our prediction model because it's powerful and versatile. It works by building multiple decision trees and merges them together to get a more accurate prediction. We chose it because: The connection between a song's audio features (like Loudness or Energy) and its streaming success is probably non-linear. Random Forest handles these complexities effectively, which simpler linear models (like Logistic Regression) often struggle with. Some features (like Loudness and Energy) are often correlated with each other. We can handle multicollinearity by using a Random Forest. A Random Forest also gives us a reliable measure of feature importance; we can see which audio characteristics (instrumentality, loudness etc.) are the most valuable predictors of virality

df = random_df
df = df.drop_duplicates()
df = df.dropna(subset=["Danceability", "Energy", "Loudness",
                  "Acousticness", "Speechiness", "Instrumentalness"])

numeric_cols = ["Danceability", "Energy", "Loudness",
                "Acousticness", "Speechiness", "Instrumentalness"]
for col in numeric_cols:
    df[col] = pd.to_numeric(df[col], errors="coerce")

df = df.dropna(subset=numeric_cols)
df["norm_engagement"] = (df["Likes"] / df["Views"]).rank(pct=True)
df["norm_conversion"] = (df["Stream"] / df["Views"]).rank(pct=True)
df["norm_streams"]    = df["Stream"].rank(pct=True)
df["viral_score"] = (
    0.5 * df["norm_engagement"] +
    0.3 * df["norm_conversion"] +
    0.2 * df["norm_streams"]
)

threshold = df["Stream"].quantile(0.80)
df["viral"] = (df["Stream"] >= threshold).astype(int)

print(df["viral"].value_counts())

X = df[["Danceability", "Energy", "Loudness",
        "Acousticness", "Speechiness", "Instrumentalness"]]
y = df["viral"]

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y, test_size=0.20, random_state=42, stratify=y
)

sm = SMOTE(random_state=42)
X_train_res, y_train_res = sm.fit_resample(X_train, y_train)

log_model = RandomForestClassifier(
    n_estimators=300,
    class_weight="balanced",
    random_state=42
)
log_model.fit(X_train_res, y_train_res)

y_pred = log_model.predict(X_test)
y_prob = log_model.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]

print("Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred))
print("\nClassification Report:\n", classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)

In[]:
thresholds = np.linspace(0,1,100)
tprs = []
fprs = []

for t in thresholds:
    preds = (y_prob >= t).astype(int)
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, preds)
    tn, fp, fn, tp = cm.ravel()
    tprs.append(tp / (tp + fn))
    fprs.append(fp / (fp + tn))

plt.figure(figsize=(7,6))
plt.plot(thresholds, tprs, label="TPR (Recall)", color="#2B8CBE", linewidth=2.5)
plt.plot(thresholds, fprs, label="FPR", color="#D95F0E", linewidth=2.5)

plt.title("Threshold Sensitivity Plot", fontsize=16, weight="bold")
plt.xlabel("Probability Threshold", fontsize=13)
plt.ylabel("Rate", fontsize=13)
plt.legend()
plt.grid(alpha=0.3)
plt.show()

The threshold sensitivity plot shows how the models behavior changes as the decision threshold moves from 0 to 1. The TPR curve highlights how recall increases at lower thresholds and decreases at higher ones, since stricter thresholds make the model predict fewer viral songs. The FPR curve rises when the threshold is low because the model becomes more willing to label a song as viral. Together, the two curves show the trade-off between identifying more viral tracks and keeping false positives low, which helps in selecting a threshold that matches the goals of the analysis.

Insights and Conclusion

It is easier for the model to know when a song is not going to be viral rather than predicting when it will be viral. The model performed strongly on the non-viral class (F1-score: 0.83) but poorly on the viral class (F1-score: 0.35). This suggests the current features are effective at filtering out songs that lack the basic ingredients for mass success, but they are insufficient to predict a hit with high confidence.

Predicting if a song is going to be viral needs a lot more parameters. The moderate overall accuracy (72.8%) and AUC (0.72) indicate that solely relying on Spotify's audio characteristics (Loudness, Energy, Danceability, etc.) is not enough. Virality is likely influenced more heavily by external factors (e.g., promotional budget, cultural trends, artist fame, specific TikTok challenges, marketing strategy, and lyrical content) which are not currently part of the audio feature set. A truly predictive model would need to incorporate these broader parameters.
